This position draws in the air into the filter tank. The air is used to oxidize iron and sulfur in the water so the filter media can remove it.

This position draws in the air and oxidizing chemical into the filter tank. The air is used to oxidize iron and sulfur in the water so the filter media can remove it. If the \"Chemical Draw\" setting is not set to 0, the minimum time for this cycle will be forced to 20 minutes. For more information on the oxidizing chemical injection see the \"Chemical Draw\" setting info button.
Enter Air Draw / Chemical Draw Cycle Time Value
Enter Air Draw Cycle Time Value

The Air Recharge Frequency sets the number of days between air recharge cycles. These cycles refill the filter tank with air, which is used to oxidize iron and other contaminates in order to filter them out of the water. This setting should always be set to 1 day, unless advised otherwise by your professional water dealer.
This position slowly opens the treatment tank to the drain. This allows air in the top of the tank to be gently released out the drain.
Enter Air Release Cycle Time Value
The average daily usage shows the average water usage over the last 30 days, excluding days when no water was used.

This position does a high rate rinse in the opposite direction of normal water flow. This rinses any physical particles filtered by the media in the unit down the drain, and on a softener unit it reorients the resin media for improved ion exchange (softening).
Enter Back Wash Cycle Time Value

This position draws in the salt brine solution from the brine tank. It is during this step the ion exchange takes place. The calcium and magnesium that has been captured by the softener resin is knocked loose by the strong brine solution and is rinsed down the drain.
Enter Brine Draw/Slow Rinse Cycle Time Value

Enabling Pre-fill will fill the Brine Tank prior to the scheduled Regeneration time to provide time for the Tank to make Brine. In some installations, the Pre-fill option reduces salt bridging and makes each regeneration cycle more consistent.

This position fills the brine tank with water so that the brine tank can make salt brine for the next regeneration cycle. Be especially careful when editing this setting as it can greatly affect efficiencies and the softeners ability to make soft water.
Enter Brine Refill Cycle Time Value

This setting determines the length of time in hours to allow the water to absorb the salt and make the brine solution in the brine tank. Typically 2-3 hours is adequate. Temperature is the biggest factor in the process. The colder the water, the longer the absorption will take.
Enter Brine Soak Duration Time Value
This position gives the chlorine that was drawn into the tank time to contact and disinfect the filter media and the filter tank.
Enter Chlorine Contact Cycle Time Value
This position is designed to use the internal pump to draw air and chlorine into the filter tank for disinfecting and sanitizing.
Enter Air / Chlorine Draw Cycle Time Value
This position is a short rinse that is used to get the chlorine that was drawn in down into the filter tank and media.
Enter Chlorine Rinse Cycle Time Value

The Days until Backwash indicates how many days are remaining until a backwash cycle occurs as a result of a day count down. The day count is decreased by one every day at the Regeneration Time. When the count decreases from 1 to 0 a backwash cycle will be started. After the cycle is complete the value will be reset to the Filter Backwash Frequency setting.

The Days until Regeneration indicates how many days are remaining until a regeneration occurs as a result of a day count down. The day count is decremented every day at the Regeneration Time. When the count decrements from 1 to 0 a regeneration will be started. After the regeneration is complete the value will be reset to the Regeneration Day Override setting.
The Filter Backwash Frequency sets the number of days between backwash cycles.

The Chemical Draw setting determines how many times the oxidizing chemical is injected into the tank during regeneration. This requires that the filter has the Oxyclean option. Setting it to 0 will disable this option. Turning this setting on will inject approximately 8 - 16oz (1 sets it to 8oz., 4 sets it to 16oz.) of the oxidizing chemical solution into the filter to disinfect the media bed and improve filtration.

This position runs a higher rate rinse in the same direction as normal water flow. This packs the resin (or filter media) bed and gets the unit ready for service by rinsing any untreated water to the drain.
Enter Rapid Rinse Cycle Time Value

The Regeneration Day Override sets the maximum number of days between regenerations. If a regeneration does not occur because of the gallons used within the set number of days, then regeneration will be forced by the Regeneration Day Override.

The Regeneration Day Override sets the maximum number of days between regenerations. If a regeneration does not occur because of the liters used within the set number of days, then regeneration will be forced by the Regeneration Day Override.

The Regeneration Time is the time of day that your unit will regenerate (or backwash). If water is used in the house during the regeneration process the unit will bypass untreated water. For that reason, the regeneration time should be set to a time of day that water use is least likely.

When using a metered softener, the meter counts the gallons of water used to determine when the resin capacity is depleted. However, because the softener should only regenerate at a certain time of the day, the reserve capacity is used to allow the softener to continue to treat water until the regeneration time occurs. The reserve capacity can be adjusted lower to use the salt more efficiently, or higher to ensure there will not be hard water breakthrough.

When using a metered softener, the meter counts the liters of water used to determine when the resin capacity is depleted. However, because the softener should only regenerate at a certain time of the day, the reserve capacity is used to allow the softener to continue to treat water until the regeneration time occurs. The reserve capacity can be adjusted lower to use the salt more efficiently, or higher to ensure there will not be hard water breakthrough.

This setting is set to the physical capacity in treatable grains of hardness that your softener can treat before needing to regenerate. This setting should only be adjusted by your professional water dealer.

This setting is set to the physical capacity in treatable grams of hardness that your softener can treat before needing to regenerate. This setting should only be adjusted by your professional water dealer.

This position is a rest position. No water runs to the drain in this position and water through the valve bypasses the treatment tank. This position is usually used to give a well time to recover after running water in another step.
Time in this position is not adjustable.

Water hardness is a measurement (in Grains per Gallon) of dissolved minerals in water. This setting should match the actual hardness measurement from a water test. Changing this setting can affect efficiencies and the softener\'s ability to make soft water.

Water hardness is a measurement (in Milligrams per liter) of dissolved minerals in water. This setting should match the actual hardness measurement from a water test. Changing this setting can affect efficiencies and the softener\'s ability to make soft water.
In order to view water usage your water treatment valve must have a water meter. On some models a water meter is optional.
